<TITLE> Former Indian lawmaker sentenced to death </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 PATNA, India, Oct 3 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A former Indian lawmaker was sentenced to death on Wednesday for killing a government official and inciting riots in eastern India more than a decade ago, officials said. His wife, also a former member of parliament, was sentenced to life in prison for being an accomplice. Anand Mohan, who was an independent MP from the eastern state of Bihar, was part of a mob that beat to death a district administrator in 1994, officials said. He was a member of parliament for three years from 1996 and is now in prison for assaulting a police officer in a separate case. Two of Mohan's local politician friends were also sentenced to death by the district judge in the state capital, Patna, in the same case. Four people, including Mohan's wife Lovely, were sentenced to life imprisonment. Mohan's lawyers said they would challenge the verdict. Many Indian politicians have criminal records, including charges of murder, rape and rioting, and a watchdog said in a report last year that more than 30 percent of lawmakers aged between 36 and 45 years faced criminal charg
